This difference in speed creates an area of lower air pressure above the rotor and higher air pressure below it, which creates the lift that keeps the helicopter in the air. Overall, helicopters are able to fly because of the unique way their rotors create lift and the tail rotor helps them to steer and maintain their balance.

question: Dependent versus independent variables I swear , I just for the life of me could never understand the difference between the two in a way that stuck with me . I need a literal ELI5 here . Please explain like I'm five.
response: 1.Independent variable: The independent variable is the variable that is being changed in order to observe its effect on the dependent variable. For example, if you want to see how the amount of sugar affects the amount of energy you have, you would change the amount of sugar you add to your drink, while keeping all other factors the same. 2. Dependent variable: The dependent variable is the variable whose value is being measured in order to see how it changes in response to the independent variable. In the example above, the dependent variable would be the amount of energy you have. 3. Control variables: The control variables are the variables that must be kept the same in order to ensure that the results are due to the independent variable and not to other factors. For example, in the sugar and energy example, you would have to keep the amount of food you eat the same, the amount of water you drink, and the amount of time you spend exercising. 4. Experiments: An experiment is when you change one variable and measure the effect it has on another variable. In this case, we have an experiment when you change the amount of sugar in your drink and measure the effect it has on your energy. 5. Statistical analysis: Statistical analysis is the process of looking at the data you have collected from an experiment in order to see if the results can be explained by the independent variable. In this case, we would look at the data from the sugar and energy experiment to see if there is a correlation between the amount of sugar and the amount of energy. 6. Conclusion: In conclusion, the independent and dependent variables are the key to understanding how an experiment works. The independent variable is the variable that is being changed, while the dependent variable is the variable whose value is being measured. Control variables must be kept the same in order to ensure accurate results. Experiments are when you change one variable and measure the effect it has on another variable, while statistical analysis is the process of looking at the data from an experiment to see if the results can be explained by the independent variable.
